    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As a former employee of a rare-book library and the fiancé of an archivist, I read "History, Digitized (and Abridged)" (March 11) with interest.</p>
        <p>Even if many archived documents are not digitized, the digital age provides a tool previous generations lacked: the so-called finding aid, an online description of an archive and its contents.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As a former employee of a rare-book library and the fiancé of an archivist, I read "History, Digitized (and Abridged)" (March 11) with interest.</p>
        <p>Even if many archived documents are not digitized, the digital age provides a tool previous generations lacked: the so-called finding aid, an online description of an archive and its contents.</p>
        <p>Archives have always been abridged for want of technology or money. But for researchers, simply knowing an artifact exists is that first step to unabridged knowledge.</p>
        <p>Andrew Whitacre  Cambridge, Mass., March 12</p>
      </block>
